        'Tamil': '<b> Superscripted Tamil </b> <br/> <br/> Tamil has a deficient script compared to other Indic scripts as it lacks distinct characters for many voiced and aspirated consonants. Publishers had to resort to the use of Superscript (and sometimes subscript) numerals to represent these letters in Tamil. <br/><br/><b> Nativization Conventions </b><br/><br/> The following nativization conventions are automatically applied to the Tamil output to increase readability. <br/> <ul> <li>Anusvara and Chandrabindu are replaced by the corresponding nasal consonant if followed by a plosive <li>Intervocalic /рои/ is replaced by /рой/',
        'Sinhala': '<b> Sanskrit/Pali Orthography in Sinhala </b> <br/><br/> When Sinhala is used to write Sanskrit/Pali text, sometimes the short e/o are used to represent the Sanskrit long e/o. For instance, <span class="sinhala">р╢▒р╢╕р╖Ь р╢╖р╢Ьр╖Ар╢нр╖Щ</span> instead of <span class="sinhala">р╢▒р╢╕р╖Э р╢╖р╢Ьр╖Ар╢нр╖Ъ</span> <br/><br/><b> Conjuncts </b> <br/><br/> Modern Sinhala does not extensively use conjuncts except for KSSA and the post-base forms of YA and RA. However, older texts, particularly for Pali/Sanskrit, extensively used conjuncts. For instance, <span class="sinhala">р╖Гр╢╕тАНр╖Кр╢╕р╖Пр╖Гр╢╕тАНр╖Кр╢╢р╖Фр╢пр╖КтАНр╢░р╖ГтАНр╖Кр╖Г</span> instead of <span class="sinhala">р╖Гр╢╕р╖Кр╢╕р╖Пр╖Гр╢╕р╖Кр╢╢р╖Фр╢пр╖Кр╢░р╖Гр╖Кр╖Г</span>. Notice the use of conjoining conjuncts such as <span class="sinhala">р╢пр╖КтАНр╢░</span> and touching letters such as <span class="sinhala">р╖ГтАНр╖Кр╖Г</span>.',
        'TamilGrantha': 'Modern Tamil only adopts /ja/, /┼Ыa/, /с╣гa/, /ha/ and the compound /┼Ыr─л/ from Grantha into its character reportoire. However, there were some attempts to use the full complimentary set of Grantha letters to fill the gaps in the Tamil script (as compared to the pan-Indic system). This was probably done instead of using superscript numerals to increase the readability of the text (and the possible wide-spread familiarity with Grantha script few decades ago). One such attempt is shown below as used in the text called <a href="http://www.archive.org/stream/bhojacharitrama00sastgoog">Bhojacharitram</a>, published in 1916. <br/><img src="../statics/Grantha_Pulli.jpg"><br/> <span class="tamilgrantha">рокрпНро░ро╛ро░рпНржзрпНропроирпНродро╕рпНроп роиро╛ро╢роЮрпН роЪ <br/>роорпБроЮрпНроЬржГ ро╕роорпНроХрпНро╖рпАропродро╛рооро┐родро┐ рее <br/>ро╡ро┐ржШрпНтАЛтАМтАНтАМрпЗроиро╢роЮрпН ро╕ роотАЛтАМтАНтАМрпЗро╣ро╢роЮрпН роЪ ред <br/>ро╣ро░ро┐роорпН роиржЧро░ро╡ро╛ро╕ро┐роиржГ <br/>роиржжрпАрокро░рпНро╡род рооро╛тАЛтАМтАНтАМрпЗро╕ржжрпБржГ <br/>ро╡ро┐рокрпНро░ро╛ тАЛтАМтАНтАМрпЗржжро╢ро╛роирпНродро░роорпН ропропрпБржГ рее</span> <br/> <br/>pr─Бrdhyantasya n─Б┼Ыa├▒ ca <br/>mu├▒jaс╕е samkс╣г─лyat─Бmiti .. <br/>vighne┼Ыa├▒ sa mahe┼Ыa├▒ ca . <br/>harim nagarav─Бsinaс╕е <br/>nad─лparvata m─Бseduс╕е <br/>vipr─Б de┼Ы─Бntaram yayuс╕е .. <br/> <br/>  For technical reasons, the above only works with the e-Grantamil font. <br/><br/> A <a href="https://groups.google.com/d/msg/mintamil/tDwV_UwYJKc/AVCkX2KQFV4J">commentary</a> on the Jaina Epic Nilakesi published in 1936 also uses this technique intermittently to disambiguate Sanskrit words that will otherwise be ambigous in the Tamil script, along with the proper Grantha script for Sanskrit quotations. There also been other recent publications that employed this method to print Sanskrit.',
        'Thaana': 'Aksharamukha automatically uses ▐З▐░ to denote gemination. When ▐З▐░ appears as a glottal stop (at the end of words), it is denoted using ╩Ф. The Arabic-specific characters in Thaana are approximated to their closest Indic counterparts.',
        'MeeteiMayek': '<b> Historic Orthography </b> <br/><br/> Historically, Meetei Mayek had characters for the following: ─л ┼л aс╕е cha ├▒a с╣нa с╣нha с╕Нa с╕Нha na ┼Ыa с╣гa :: <span class="meeteimayek">ъпСълл ъпСълм ъпСъл╡ ълв ълг ълд ъле ълж ълз ъпЕ ълй ълк</span>. But, they are not in vogue any more. By default, Aksharamukha does not use these characters. They are replaced by their closest approximations: i u ah ca na ta tha da dha na sa sa :: <span class="meeteimayek">ъпП ъпО ъпСъпНъпн ъпЖ ъпЕ ъпЗ ъпК ъпЧ ъпЩ ъпЕ ъпБ ъпБ</span>. The historic characters are used only if the <i>preserve script</i> option is enabled.',
