        'Urdu': 'Urdu is an abjad. It amounts to short-vowels being not written and /v/ and /y/ also denoting long vowels. (The following assumes the consonats have an inherent /a/ like Indic scripts for illustration.). In the absense of short vowels, /ava/ can stand for /va/, /┼л/, /o/ or /au/, /aya/ can stand for /ya/, /─л/, /e/ or /ai/. On the same note /kava/ could be /kava/, /k┼л/, /ko/, /kau/ and /kaya/ could be /kaya/, /k─л/, /ke/ or /kai/, Thus /kayarala/ probably should be read /kerala/ and /hayadar─Бb─Бd/ as /haidar─Бb─Бd/. Additionally, the short-vowels (i/u) have to be guessed by context. As in North-Indic scripts, the Schwa deletion is also not shown explicitly. Ideally, /urd┼л/ should be written as /╪з┘П╪▒┘Т╪п┘П┘И/ but it is often written as /╪з╪▒╪п┘И/ (aradava). One should know that the first vowel is a short /u/, the schwa /a/ in r is deleted, and /va/ in this case denotes /┼л/. Thus giving the reading <s>a</s><sup>u</sup>r<s>a</s>d<s>(ava)</s><sup>┼л</sup>. /┘Е█М┌║/ (mayaс╣Г) must be read m<s>(aya)</s><sup>e</sup>с╣Г /meс╣Г/, /█Б┘Ж╪п┘И╪│╪к╪з┘Ж/ (hanadavasat─Бna) is read h<s>a</s><sup>i</sup>n<s>a</s>d<s>(ava)</s><sup>┼л</sup>s<s>a</s>t─Бn<s>a</s> /hind┼лst─Бn/.<br/><br/> Aksharamukha approximates the Arabic-specific consonants to their nearest Indic counterparts and Hamza is shown with an underscore. Ayin is mapped to /a/. Fathatan becomes just an /n/.',
